    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Hey, I'm studying for my accounting exam and I'm stuck on depreciation. Can you explain the formula for straight-line depreciation and give me an example? Let's say a company buys a piece of heavy machinery for $50,000, it has a salvage value of $5,000, and a useful life of 5 years. How would you calculate that?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The straight-line depreciation formula calculates expense by dividing the depreciable base (Cost minus Salvage Value) by the useful life in years. For your machinery, the depreciable base is $45,000 ($50,000 cost - $5,000 salvage), which you divide by the 5-year life to find an annual expense. This results in a consistent depreciation charge of $9,000 each year for the entire five-year period.",
      "source": "target",
